From 3ced0db3eb9625f20de6363c14b12013a6d43c56 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Thirusenthil Kumaran J <thirusen@qti.qualcomm.com>
Date: Thu, 14 Aug 2025 10:21:33 +0530
Subject: [PATCH] UPSTREAM:CP: wifi: ath12k: Update peer puncture pattern
 correctly

Currently, the puncture pattern of the peer is sent to the firmware
as part of the peer assoc WMI command.

Consider a case, the AP is operating in a 5 GHz channel 36 with a BW
of 80 MHz. Now, a channel switch is initiated to same 5 GHz channel 36,
BW 80 MHz, but with a puncture pattern of 0x8. This puncture pattern is
sent correctly to the firmware as part of the WMI comamnd
'WMI_PDEV_MULTIPLE_VDEV_RESTART_REQUEST_CMDID'.
However, the pattern is not updated correctly for the connected peers
after MVR. Thus, host sends the older pattern (0x0 in this case) to the
FW. This causes the FW to send packets in 80 MHz full BW, even though 20
MHz is punctured.

There are two issues here:
(1) The target channel's puncture pattern is not updated in the arvif
    structure after MVR. So, any new STA that tries to connect to the
    AP will use the old pattern.
(2) 'WMI_PEER_CHAN_WIDTH_SWITCH_CMDID' is not sent to the FW
    after MVR for the connected peers. So the FW is not informed about
    any changes to the peer's channel width or puncture pattern.
    Peer channel width switch WMI command will be sent only if the
    'IEEE80211_RC_BW_CHANGED' flag is set. Currently, this flag is
    not set due to an early return due to pending CSA check after MVR.

To fix this,
(1) Update the target channel's puncture pattern in the arvif
    structure after MVR.
(2) Set the changed flag 'IEEE80211_RC_BW_CHANGED', if there is a
    change in the puncture pattern after a successful MVR irrespective
    of any other condition. This will ensure that the
    'WMI_PEER_CHAN_WIDTH_SWITCH_CMDID' is sent to the FW for all the
    connected peers.

Fixes: Ia3eca0b5d02 ("CP: wifi: ath12k: PKG upgrade changes set 10")
Patch-work: None
Tag: PEER_HANDLING
Patch-dependency:
ath12k/0279-003-ath12k-fix-RU-puncturing-pattern-for-peers-after-CSA.patch

Signed-off-by: Thirusenthil Kumaran J <thirusen@qti.qualcomm.com>
---
 drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath12k/mac.c | 5 ++++-
 1 file changed, 4 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath12k/mac.c b/drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath12k/mac.c
index 34fc4fcb5459..b034b2a86202 100644
--- a/drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath12k/mac.c
+++ b/drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath12k/mac.c
@@ -16969,9 +16969,10 @@ static int ath12k_vdev_restart_sequence(struct ath12k_link_vif *arvif,
 	}
 
 beacon_tmpl_setup:
+
+	ath12k_mac_update_ru_punct_bitmap(arvif, &old_chanctx, new_ctx);
 	if (arvif->pending_csa_up)
 		return 0;
-	ath12k_mac_update_ru_punct_bitmap(arvif, &old_chanctx, new_ctx);
 
 	if (!arvif->is_up)
 		return -EOPNOTSUPP;
@@ -17384,6 +17385,8 @@ ath12k_mac_update_vif_chan_mvr(struct ath12k *ar,
 			continue;
 		}
 
+		arvif->punct_bitmap = vifs[i].new_ctx->def.punctured;
+
 		if (!ath12k_mac_is_bridge_vdev(arvif) &&
 		    vifs[i].link_conf->mbssid_tx_vif &&
 		    ahvif == (struct ath12k_vif *)vifs[i].link_conf->mbssid_tx_vif->drv_priv) {
-- 
